[2025-08-24T01:53:50.146Z] [INFO] Received stdin input: {"session_id":"a3c51241-8e08-4ad2-a583-4736d475cdcf","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\tamtr\\.claude\\projects\\D--sources-demo-eye-rest\\a3c51241-8e08-4ad2-a583-4736d475cdcf.jsonl","cwd":"D:\\sources\\demo\\eye-rest","hook_event_name":"PostToolUse","tool_name":"WebSearch","tool_input":{"query":"WPF DispatcherTimer unit testing C# xUnit STAFact best practices 2024"},"tool_response":{"query":"WPF DispatcherTimer unit testing C# xUnit STAFact best practices 2024","results":["I'll search for information about unit testing WPF DispatcherTimer with C# xUnit STAFact and best practices from 2024.",{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Lr5z1AmksgtKR43xpn2byv","content":[{"title":"GitHub - AArnott/Xunit.StaFact: Run your xunit-based tests on an STA thread with the WPF Dispatcher, a WinForms SynchronizationContext, or even a cross-platform generic UI thread emulation with a SynchronizationContext that keeps code running on a \"main thread\" for that test.","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact"},{"title":"How to Test a Class Which Uses DispatcherTimer - CodeProject","url":"https://www.codeproject.com/Articles/19597/How-to-Test-a-Class-Which-Uses-DispatcherTimer"},{"title":"NuGet Gallery | Xunit.StaFact 2.1.7","url":"https://www.nuget.org/packages/Xunit.StaFact/"},{"title":"c# - How can I test a class that uses DispatcherTimer? - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38083711/how-can-i-test-a-class-that-uses-dispatchertimer"},{"title":"WPF unit test improvements for .NET 10 · Issue #10085 · dotnet/wpf","url":"https://github.com/dotnet/wpf/issues/10085"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact 2.1.7 on NuGet - Libraries.io - security & maintenance data for open source software","url":"https://libraries.io/nuget/Xunit.StaFact"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact/README.md at main · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/blob/main/README.md"},{"title":"Releases · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/releases"},{"title":"[WPF] Unit Tests mit DispatcherTimer - .NET - Fachinformatiker.de","url":"https://www.fachinformatiker.de/topic/151924-wpf-unit-tests-mit-dispatchertimer/"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact/docfx/docs/getting-started.md at main · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/blob/main/docfx/docs/getting-started.md/"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the best practices for unit testing WPF DispatcherTimer with C# xUnit and STAFact in 2024:\n\n## Key Best Practices\n\n### 1. Use Xunit.StaFact Package\n\nThe recommended approach is to use the Xunit.StaFact NuGet package and simply use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\n### 2. Choose the Right Attribute\n\nUse [WpfFact] specifically for WPF tests as it provides the WPF Dispatcher, or use [StaFact] for general STA thread tests, or [UIFact] for cross-platform scenarios.(no content)Theory variants of these attributes allow for parameterized testing.\n\n### 3. Understanding DispatcherTimer Testing Challenges\n\nKey issues when testing DispatcherTimer include:\n- Threads that run unit tests do not have an active Dispatcher by default.\n- The method which activates a Dispatcher is a blocking call, so you cannot execute any code which follows that method call until the Dispatcher is shut down.\n- You need to shut down a thread's Dispatcher for a unit test method to complete.\n- Once you shut down a thread's Dispatcher, you cannot restart it or give the thread a new Dispatcher.\n\n### 4. Consider Abstraction Over Direct DispatcherTimer Use\n\nIt's best if you can avoid DispatcherTimer in your system under test and use an abstraction instead (Rx has a nice one called IScheduler).(no content)This kind of abstraction allows you to explicitly control the flow of time in your unit tests, rather than making your tests conditional on CPU timings.\n\n### 5. Example Test Implementation\n\nHere's a basic example structure using WpfFact:\n\n[UIFact] or [WpfFact] allows async tests that maintain the STA thread context and ensure the thread remains consistent even after await operations.\n\n### 6. Message Pump Requirements\n\nFor all of this to work properly the Dispatcher associated with the DispatcherTimer must be running; its message pump must be \"pumping\".(no content)If you don't have proper STA thread setup with message pumping and a proper Dispatcher installed, the timer messages won't be processed.\n\n### 7. Priority Considerations\n\nThe default priority given to a DispatcherTimer's tick message in a message queue is so low that the tick messages are never processed by the message pump in some environments like console applications and NUnit GUI.\n\n## Latest Updates (2024)\n\nThe .NET team has been working on WPF unit test improvements, including getting xunit working with dispatcher support. The Xunit.StaFact package continues to be actively maintained and is the standard solution for this scenario.\n\nThese practices ensure that your DispatcherTimer-dependent code can be properly tested in an environment that closely matches the actual WPF application runtime conditions."],"durationSeconds":35.53498479999974}}
