github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/releases"},{"title":"[WPF] Unit Tests mit DispatcherTimer - .NET - Fachinformatiker.de","url":"https://www.fachinformatiker.de/topic/151924-wpf-unit-tests-mit-dispatchertimer/"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact/docfx/docs/getting-started.md at main · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/blob/main/docfx/docs/getting-started.md/"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the best practices for unit testing WPF DispatcherTimer with C# xUnit and STAFact in 2024:\n\n## Key Best Practices\n\n### 1. Use Xunit.StaFact Package\n\nThe recommended approach is to use the Xunit.StaFact NuGet package and simply use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\n### 2. Choose the Right Attribute\n\nUse [WpfFact] specifically for WPF tests as it provides the WPF Dispatcher, or use [StaFact] for general STA thread tests, or [UIFact] for cross-platform scenarios.(no content)Theory variants of these attributes allow for parameterized testing.\n\n### 3. Understanding DispatcherTimer Testing Challenges\n\nKey issues when testing DispatcherTimer include:\n- Threads that run unit tests do not have an active Dispatcher by default.\n- The method which activates a Dispatcher is a blocking call, so you cannot execute any code which follows that method call until the Dispatcher is shut down.\n- You need to shut down a thread's Dispatcher for a unit test method to complete.\n- Once you shut down a thread's Dispatcher, you cannot restart it or give the thread a new Dispatcher.\n\n### 4. Consider Abstraction Over Direct DispatcherTimer Use\n\nIt's best if you can avoid DispatcherTimer in your system under test and use an abstraction instead (Rx has a nice one called IScheduler).(no content)This kind of abstraction allows you to explicitly control the flow of time in your unit tests, rather than making your tests conditional on CPU timings.\n\n### 5. Example Test Implementation\n\nHere's a basic example structure using WpfFact:\n\n[UIFact] or [WpfFact] allows async tests that maintain the STA thread context and ensure the thread remains consistent even after await operations.\n\n### 6. Message Pump Requirements\n\nFor all of this to work properly the Dispatcher associated with the DispatcherTimer must be running; its message pump must be \"pumping\".(no content)If you don't have proper STA thread setup with message pumping and a proper Dispatcher installed, the timer messages won't be processed.\n\n### 7. Priority Considerations\n\nThe default priority given to a DispatcherTimer's tick message in a message queue is so low that the tick messages are never processed by the message pump in some environments like console applications and NUnit GUI.\n\n## Latest Updates (2024)\n\nThe .NET team has been working on WPF unit test improvements, including getting xunit working with dispatcher support. The Xunit.StaFact package continues to be actively maintained and is the standard solution for this scenario.\n\nThese practices ensure that your DispatcherTimer-dependent code can be properly tested in an environment that closely matches the actual WPF application runtime conditions."],"durationSeconds":35.53498479999974}}
[2025-08-24T01:54:29.306Z] [INFO] Received stdin input: {"session_id":"a3c51241-8e08-4ad2-a583-4736d475cdcf","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\tamtr\\.claude\\projects\\D--sources-demo-eye-rest\\a3c51241-8e08-4ad2-a583-4736d475cdcf.jsonl","cwd":"D:\\sources\\demo\\eye-rest","hook_event_name":"PostToolUse","tool_name":"WebSearch","tool_input":{"query":"\"Xunit.StaFact\" WPF DispatcherTimer testing examples C# async await TaskCompletionSource"},"tool_response":{"query":"\"Xunit.StaFact\" WPF DispatcherTimer testing examples C# async await TaskCompletionSource","results":["I'll search for information about testing WPF DispatcherTimer with Xunit.StaFact using async/await and TaskCompletionSource in C#.",{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01CnmsFWYnQ2UBZxk3ZHFsUS","content":[{"title":"GitHub - AArnott/Xunit.StaFact: Run your xunit-based tests on an STA thread with the WPF Dispatcher, a WinForms SynchronizationContext, or even a cross-platform generic UI thread emulation with a SynchronizationContext that keeps code running on a \"main thread\" for that test.","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact 2.1.7 on NuGet - Libraries.io - security & maintenance data for open source software","url":"https://libraries.io/nuget/Xunit.StaFact"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact/README.md at main · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/blob/main/README.md"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact | based tests on an STA thread","url":"https://kandi.openweaver.com/csharp/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact"},{"title":"Xunit.StaFact/UITestInvoker.cs at main · AArnott/Xunit.StaFact","url":"https://github.com/AArnott/Xunit.StaFact/blob/main/src/Xunit.StaFact/Sdk/UITestInvoker.cs"},{"title":"NuGet Gallery | Xunit.StaFact 2.1.7","url":"https://www.nuget.org/packages/Xunit.StaFact/"},{"title":"multithreading - Problems running multiple xunit tests under STA Thread WPF - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/67647877/problems-running-multiple-xunit-tests-under-sta-thread-wpf"}]},"Based on the search results, I can provide you with information about using Xunit.StaFact for testing WPF components including DispatcherTimer with async/await patterns.\n\n## Xunit.StaFact Overview\n\nXunit.StaFact is a library that allows you to run xunit-based tests on an STA thread with the WPF Dispatcher, a WinForms SynchronizationContext, or even a cross-platform generic UI thread emulation. You can simply use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\n## Basic Usage Example\n\nHere's a basic example of how to use Xunit.StaFact with async/await:\n\n```csharp\n[UIFact] // or [WinFormsFact] or [WpfFact]\npublic async Task WpfFact_OnSTAThread()\n{\n    Assert.Equal(ApartmentState.STA, Thread.CurrentThread.GetApartmentState());\n    int originalThread = Environment.CurrentManagedThreadId;\n    await Task.Yield();\n    Assert.Equal(originalThread, Environment.CurrentManagedThreadId); // still there\n}\n```\n\n## Key Features\n\n1. **Attribute Options**: You can use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] attributes. Theory variants of these attributes allow for parameterized testing.\n\n2. **SynchronizationContext Support**: The library provides a private SynchronizationContext that works cross-platform and effectively keeps code running on the test's starting thread the way a GUI application's main thread would do.\n\n3. **Platform Compatibility**: STA thread only applies on Windows. On other operating systems, an MTA thread is used. Windows-only attributes result in the test to result in \"Skipped\" on other operating systems.\n\n## Important Considerations for WPF Testing\n\nWhen using Xunit.StaFact for WPF testing, there can be issues when running multiple tests, particularly when checking Application.Current.Windows in assertions. Tests may fail with \"System.InvalidOperationException: The calling thread cannot access this object because a different thread owns it\" when run together, even though they pass individually.(no content)For tests that need WPF to process events or timers, avoid synchronously blocking with Thread.Sleep. Instead, make the test method async and use await to give WPF time to process.\n\n## Installation\n\nThe package is available on NuGet as Xunit.StaFact. Simply install it and use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\nFor testing DispatcherTimer specifically with TaskCompletionSource, you would typically:\n1. Use the [WpfFact] attribute on your test method\n2. Create a TaskCompletionSource to handle async completion\n3. Set up your DispatcherTimer within the test\n4. Use await with the TaskCompletionSource.Task to wait for timer events\n5. Assert your expected behavior\n\nThis approach ensures your tests run on the proper STA thread with a WPF Dispatcher available, making it possible to test WPF-specific components like DispatcherTimer in a unit test environment."],"durationSeconds":34.583345800001176}}
