der-sta-thread-wpf"}]},"Based on the search results, I can provide you with information about using Xunit.StaFact for testing WPF components including DispatcherTimer with async/await patterns.\n\n## Xunit.StaFact Overview\n\nXunit.StaFact is a library that allows you to run xunit-based tests on an STA thread with the WPF Dispatcher, a WinForms SynchronizationContext, or even a cross-platform generic UI thread emulation. You can simply use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\n## Basic Usage Example\n\nHere's a basic example of how to use Xunit.StaFact with async/await:\n\n```csharp\n[UIFact] // or [WinFormsFact] or [WpfFact]\npublic async Task WpfFact_OnSTAThread()\n{\n    Assert.Equal(ApartmentState.STA, Thread.CurrentThread.GetApartmentState());\n    int originalThread = Environment.CurrentManagedThreadId;\n    await Task.Yield();\n    Assert.Equal(originalThread, Environment.CurrentManagedThreadId); // still there\n}\n```\n\n## Key Features\n\n1. **Attribute Options**: You can use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or the cross-platform [UIFact] attributes. Theory variants of these attributes allow for parameterized testing.\n\n2. **SynchronizationContext Support**: The library provides a private SynchronizationContext that works cross-platform and effectively keeps code running on the test's starting thread the way a GUI application's main thread would do.\n\n3. **Platform Compatibility**: STA thread only applies on Windows. On other operating systems, an MTA thread is used. Windows-only attributes result in the test to result in \"Skipped\" on other operating systems.\n\n## Important Considerations for WPF Testing\n\nWhen using Xunit.StaFact for WPF testing, there can be issues when running multiple tests, particularly when checking Application.Current.Windows in assertions. Tests may fail with \"System.InvalidOperationException: The calling thread cannot access this object because a different thread owns it\" when run together, even though they pass individually.(no content)For tests that need WPF to process events or timers, avoid synchronously blocking with Thread.Sleep. Instead, make the test method async and use await to give WPF time to process.\n\n## Installation\n\nThe package is available on NuGet as Xunit.StaFact. Simply install it and use [WpfFact], [WinFormsFact], [StaFact] or [UIFact] on your test method to run your test under conditions that most closely match the main thread in your application.\n\nFor testing DispatcherTimer specifically with TaskCompletionSource, you would typically:\n1. Use the [WpfFact] attribute on your test method\n2. Create a TaskCompletionSource to handle async completion\n3. Set up your DispatcherTimer within the test\n4. Use await with the TaskCompletionSource.Task to wait for timer events\n5. Assert your expected behavior\n\nThis approach ensures your tests run on the proper STA thread with a WPF Dispatcher available, making it possible to test WPF-specific components like DispatcherTimer in a unit test environment."],"durationSeconds":34.583345800001176}}
