page that opens, scroll to Advanced settings, then set Audio enhancements to Off from the dropdown menu.(no content)If multiple audio output devices are available, check that you have the appropriate one selected.(no content)Since the sound seems to be in a compressed format, it has to be decompressed before you can play it using SoundPlayer. You can use Windows Audio Compression Manager to decompress the sound for playback - though for SystemSounds this shouldn't typically be an issue.\n\n## Registry and Group Policy\n\nHave you checked the registry keys shown in the tutorial towards the end?(no content)Windows key + R, gpedit.msc opens the group policy editor. If any are set you may also see text in red in Settings \"Some settings are managed by....\"\n\n## Alternative Workarounds\n\nYou can change the sound scheme for Windows to \"No Sounds\", so even though it's not muted in the mixer, system sounds will not play. - This is the opposite of what you want, but indicates sound scheme settings are important.\n\nOne was fixed by creating a new user account. - This can help determine if it's a user-specific issue.\n\nThe most common causes are muted System Sounds in the Volume Mixer, incorrect sound scheme settings, or disabled audio enhancements interfering with playback."],"durationSeconds":31.101218899999978}}
[2025-09-20T20:16:51.395Z] [INFO] Received stdin input: {"session_id":"90241b75-5090-4df7-989a-d94b8d758310","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\tamtr\\.claude\\projects\\D--sources-demo-eye-rest\\90241b75-5090-4df7-989a-d94b8d758310.jsonl","cwd":"D:\\sources\\demo\\eye-rest","permission_mode":"bypassPermissions","hook_event_name":"PostToolUse","tool_name":"WebSearch","tool_input":{"query":"\"System.Media.SystemSounds\" \"Play()\" not working C# .NET Windows audio troubleshoot Volume Mixer \"System Sounds\""},"tool_response":{"query":"\"System.Media.SystemSounds\" \"Play()\" not working C# .NET Windows audio troubleshoot Volume Mixer \"System Sounds\"","results":["I'll search for information about troubleshooting System.Media.SystemSounds Play() method issues in C# .NET, particularly related to Windows audio and Volume Mixer system sounds.",{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Eh3vNy73TvVB3Mn6NGjEpg","content":[{"title":"c# - SystemSounds Play not working - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/343790/systemsounds-play-not-working"},{"title":"Windows 10 Not Playing System Sounds. All Other Sounds Are Okay. Solved - Windows 10 Forums","url":"https://www.tenforums.com/sound-audio/126126-windows-10-not-playing-system-sounds-all-other-sounds-okay.html"},{"title":"SystemSounds Class (System.Media) | Microsoft Learn","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.media.systemsounds?view=windowsdesktop-9.0"},{"title":"windows 7 - Computer Playing sounds but not showing action on Volume Mixer - Super User","url":"https://superuser.com/questions/599647/computer-playing-sounds-but-not-showing-action-on-volume-mixer"},{"title":"audio - Windows 10 Volume Mixer fails to keep System Sounds muted over Remote Desktop Connection - Super User","url":"https://superuser.com/questions/1119689/windows-10-volume-mixer-fails-to-keep-system-sounds-muted-over-remote-desktop-co"},{"title":"SoundPlayer Class (System.Media) | Microsoft Learn","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.media.soundplayer?view=windowsdesktop-9.0"},{"title":"c# - Playing Windows System Sounds with System.Media.SoundPlayer - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22123899/playing-windows-system-sounds-with-system-media-soundplayer"},{"title":"c# - SystemSounds only plays one sound - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54294967/systemsounds-only-plays-one-sound"},{"title":"Application not appearing in the volume mixer - Microsoft Q&A","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/52c09680-4b39-490a-973d-7a880b8cce04/application-not-appearing-in-the-volume-mixer?forum=windows-all"},{"title":"c# - Controlling Volume Mixer - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14306048/controlling-volume-mixer"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the key troubleshooting steps and solutions for System.Media.SystemSounds.Play() not working in C# .NET Windows applications:\n\n## Common Issues and Solutions\n\n### 1. Registry Corruption Issue\nThis is a common problem that's unrelated to the .NET Play calls - while sounds can be played/previewed from the Control Panel Sounds and Audio Devices applet, they don't play when programs trigger them, often due to corruption caused by program installations. \n\nThe fix involves checking the registry: The (Default) entry for HKEY_CURRENT_USER should be \"(value not set)\". If it's something else (like \"OfficeCompleted\"), delete the entry and it will be re-created as \"(value not set)\".\n\n### 2. Volume Mixer Settings\nCheck the Volume Mixer by clicking on the volume bar for \"System Sounds\" in the \"Applications\" section - if nothing plays there but everything else plays fine, even after setting System Sounds to full volume, this indicates a mixer issue.\n\n### 3. Windows Sound Scheme Settings\nAs a workaround, you can change the Windows sound scheme - right click the volume icon in the toolbar, click Sounds, and ensure the Sound Scheme is not set to \"No Sounds\". The sounds associated with each type of operating system sound event can be configured in Windows Control Panel.\n\n### 4. Simple Restart Solution\nSometimes a simple restart fixes the issue - System.Media.SystemSounds.Beep.Play() and System.Console.Beep() may not work until after a reboot.\n\n### 5. Technical Details\nSystemSounds internally uses the Win32 MessageBeep API method, passing the sound type (e.g. 0x40 for Asterisk) to the Windows MessageBeep function. SystemSounds provides static methods to access sounds associated with Asterisk, Beep, Exclamation, Hand and Question sound events, each returning a SystemSound that can be used to play the sound.\n\n### 6. User Account Specific Issues\nIf system sounds work when creating a new user account and testing there, this indicates the problem is user-profile specific rather than a driver issue.\n\n## Recommended Troubleshooting Order:\n1. First try a system restart\n2. Check Volume Mixer to ensure System Sounds aren't muted\n3. Verify Windows Sound Scheme isn't set to \"No Sounds\"\n4. Check the registry for corruption (HKEY_CURRENT_USER default value)\n5. Test with a different user account to isolate profile-specific issues\n6. Ensure the specific system sounds are configured in Control Panel > Sounds\n\nIf none of these solutions work, consider using the System.Media.SoundPlayer class with custom .wav files as an alternative to SystemSounds."],"durationSeconds":28.678465299999925}}
