m/en-us/dotnet/api/system.media.soundplayer?view=windowsdesktop-9.0"},{"title":"c# - Playing Windows System Sounds with System.Media.SoundPlayer - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22123899/playing-windows-system-sounds-with-system-media-soundplayer"},{"title":"c# - SystemSounds only plays one sound - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54294967/systemsounds-only-plays-one-sound"},{"title":"Application not appearing in the volume mixer - Microsoft Q&A","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/52c09680-4b39-490a-973d-7a880b8cce04/application-not-appearing-in-the-volume-mixer?forum=windows-all"},{"title":"c# - Controlling Volume Mixer - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14306048/controlling-volume-mixer"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the key troubleshooting steps and solutions for System.Media.SystemSounds.Play() not working in C# .NET Windows applications:\n\n## Common Issues and Solutions\n\n### 1. Registry Corruption Issue\nThis is a common problem that's unrelated to the .NET Play calls - while sounds can be played/previewed from the Control Panel Sounds and Audio Devices applet, they don't play when programs trigger them, often due to corruption caused by program installations. \n\nThe fix involves checking the registry: The (Default) entry for HKEY_CURRENT_USER should be \"(value not set)\". If it's something else (like \"OfficeCompleted\"), delete the entry and it will be re-created as \"(value not set)\".\n\n### 2. Volume Mixer Settings\nCheck the Volume Mixer by clicking on the volume bar for \"System Sounds\" in the \"Applications\" section - if nothing plays there but everything else plays fine, even after setting System Sounds to full volume, this indicates a mixer issue.\n\n### 3. Windows Sound Scheme Settings\nAs a workaround, you can change the Windows sound scheme - right click the volume icon in the toolbar, click Sounds, and ensure the Sound Scheme is not set to \"No Sounds\". The sounds associated with each type of operating system sound event can be configured in Windows Control Panel.\n\n### 4. Simple Restart Solution\nSometimes a simple restart fixes the issue - System.Media.SystemSounds.Beep.Play() and System.Console.Beep() may not work until after a reboot.\n\n### 5. Technical Details\nSystemSounds internally uses the Win32 MessageBeep API method, passing the sound type (e.g. 0x40 for Asterisk) to the Windows MessageBeep function. SystemSounds provides static methods to access sounds associated with Asterisk, Beep, Exclamation, Hand and Question sound events, each returning a SystemSound that can be used to play the sound.\n\n### 6. User Account Specific Issues\nIf system sounds work when creating a new user account and testing there, this indicates the problem is user-profile specific rather than a driver issue.\n\n## Recommended Troubleshooting Order:\n1. First try a system restart\n2. Check Volume Mixer to ensure System Sounds aren't muted\n3. Verify Windows Sound Scheme isn't set to \"No Sounds\"\n4. Check the registry for corruption (HKEY_CURRENT_USER default value)\n5. Test with a different user account to isolate profile-specific issues\n6. Ensure the specific system sounds are configured in Control Panel > Sounds\n\nIf none of these solutions work, consider using the System.Media.SoundPlayer class with custom .wav files as an alternative to SystemSounds."],"durationSeconds":28.678465299999925}}
[2025-09-20T20:17:27.159Z] [INFO] Received stdin input: {"session_id":"90241b75-5090-4df7-989a-d94b8d758310","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\tamtr\\.claude\\projects\\D--sources-demo-eye-rest\\90241b75-5090-4df7-989a-d94b8d758310.jsonl","cwd":"D:\\sources\\demo\\eye-rest","permission_mode":"bypassPermissions","hook_event_name":"PostToolUse","tool_name":"WebSearch","tool_input":{"query":"Windows Volume Mixer \"System Sounds\" muted disabled C# WPF audio not playing registry fix HKEY_CURRENT_USER"},"tool_response":{"query":"Windows Volume Mixer \"System Sounds\" muted disabled C# WPF audio not playing registry fix HKEY_CURRENT_USER","results":["I'll search for information about fixing Windows Volume Mixer system sounds issues, particularly related to C# WPF audio not playing and registry solutions.",{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01V7iULchkKRM33z69Aj3snp","content":[{"title":"Volume Mixer: Can't Control Individual Application Volume - Microsoft Q&A","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/4258641/volume-mixer-cant-control-individual-application-v"},{"title":"audio - Windows 10 Volume Mixer fails to keep System Sounds muted over Remote Desktop Connection - Super User","url":"https://superuser.com/questions/1119689/windows-10-volume-mixer-fails-to-keep-system-sounds-muted-over-remote-desktop-co"},{"title":"winforms - Mute Windows Volume using C# - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/154089/mute-windows-volume-using-c-sharp"},{"title":"c# - How to mute or adjust volume on windows systems sounds? - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/71211059/how-to-mute-or-adjust-volume-on-windows-systems-sounds"},{"title":"c# - Controlling Volume Mixer - Stack Overflow","url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14306048/controlling-volume-mixer"},{"title":"How to disable Windows system sounds - permanently - but not application sound - Super User","url":"https://superuser.com/questions/134315/how-to-disable-windows-system-sounds-permanently-but-not-application-sound"},{"title":"windows 10 - Where are the volume mixer startup options? Is there in regedit? - Super User","url":"https://superuser.com/questions/1106305/where-are-the-volume-mixer-startup-options-is-there-in-regedit"},{"title":"How To Mute Just Windows System (Sounds)?","url":"https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/exchange/en-US/9a5ff0d7-7d35-4cb2-bcfd-e4c694641a81/how-to-mute-just-windows-system-sounds"},{"title":"How to programmatically change an application audio volume attached to Windows Audio mixer - Microsoft Q&A","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/1182393/how-to-programmatically-change-an-application-audi"},{"title":"How to fix Volume Mixer is muting programs individually on ...","url":"https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/all/how-to-fix-volume-mixer-is-muting-programs/fb8dfc52-e9b3-4c7f-b279-544482342261"}]},"Based on the search results, I found several relevant solutions for fixing Windows Volume Mixer system sounds issues, particularly when they're muted or disabled, and how to control them programmatically in C# WPF applications. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Registry Solutions for Volume Mixer Issues\n\nThe audio settings per application can be found in the registry at: HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Internet Explorer\\LowRegistry\\Audio\\PolicyConfig\\PropertyStore(no content)In the Windows Registry, all the system sounds are stored under HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\AppEvents\\Schemes\\Apps. Under Apps are several folders, and under each of those folders are more folders, and lastly, under each one of those is another folder called \".Current\". This folder's default value is what is used by the system. To turn off a system sound, simply set the value of all the .Current folders to an empty string.\n\n## Registry Fix for Volume Mixer Not Working\n\nIf the Volume Mixer is not controlling individual applications properly, there's a specific registry fix:\n\nIn the Start menu search bar, search for registry editor and select Run as administrator. Navigate to HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE > SOFTWARE> Microsoft > Windows NT. Right-click Current Version and select New key. Name it MTCUVC. Right-click MTCUVC > New > DWORD (32-bit) Value. Right-click the newly created sub-key and select Rename. Name it EnableMtcUvc. Set Value to 0 and Base to Hexadecimal.\n\n## C# WPF Solutions for Controlling System Sounds\n\nFor programmatically controlling system sounds and application volumes in C# WPF:\n\n1. **Using NAudio Library**: You can use NAudio.CoreAudioApi.MMDeviceEnumerator to enumerate and control audio devices, including muting them with dev.AudioEndpointVolume.Mute = true\n\n2. **Using Windows Messages**: You can send Windows messages to toggle mute using SendMessageW with WM_APPCOMMAND and APPCOMMAND_VOLUME_MUTE. In WPF, use new WindowInteropHelper(this).Handle to get the window handle\n\n3. **Controlling Individual Application Volumes**: You can use ISimpleAudioVolume interface to control individual application volumes through the Windows audio session manager, allowing you to SetMute, SetMasterVolume, GetMute, and GetMasterVolume for specific applications\n\n## Alternative Solutions\n\n1. **Reset Audio Settings**: Go to System > Sound > App volume and device preferences. Click the Reset button. Check if you can now open the volume mixer.\n\n2. **Change Sound Scheme**: You can change the sound scheme for Windows to \"No Sounds\", so even though it's not muted in the mixer, system sounds will not play.\n\n3. **Per-Application Volume Control**: In Windows Vista and later, you can control per-application sounds, including system sounds. Click the volume icon in the taskbar, then click on \"mixer\". Click the mute button under \"System sounds\". Applications' sounds will still play, but system sounds will not.\n\n## Registry Location to Prevent Sound Scheme Changes\n\nTo disable all sounds permanently, save this as a .reg file: [HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Personalization] \"NoChangingSoundScheme\"=dword:00000001\n\nThese solutions should help resolve issues where system sounds are muted or disabled in the Windows Volume Mixer, and provide ways to programmatically control audio in C# WPF applications."],"durationSeconds":32.04183440000005}}
